h3. Summary  

* When filtering a Project Picker custom field in Jira on a Jira Issue macro, in Confluence, it will display the ID of the project instead of the name of it. 

h3. Steps to Reproduce 
# In Jira, choose *Settings >> Issues*;
# Select *Fields >> Custom fields*
# Click on *Add custom field*;
# Click on *Advanced >> Project Picker (single project)*;
# Give a name to it and click on the *Create* button;
# Create an issue in Jira and add this field to it;
# In Confluence, create a page;
# On the Confluence page, insert a Jira Issue macro;
# On the macro's settings, click on *Display options*;
# On the *Columns to display* field, type the name that was given to the Jira custom field;
# Click on the *Insert* button;
# *Publish* the page;

h3. Expected Results  
* Confluence will display the name of the project on the column associated with the Project Picker custom field.

h3. Actual Results 
* Confluence displays the ID of the project on the Jira Issue macro, instead of the project's name

h3.Workaround 
N/A

h3. Summary

* When filtering a Checkbox custom field in Jira on a Jira Issue macro, in Confluence, it will display a string with all the options listed, without spaces to identify which are the options distinctively.

h3. Steps to Reproduce 
# In Jira, choose *Settings >> Issues*;
# Select *Fields >> Custom fields*
# Click on *Add custom field*;
# Click on *Standard >> Checkboxes*;
# Give a name to it and add some options to it;
# Click on the *Create* button;
# Create an issue in Jira and add this field to it;
# In Confluence, create a page;
# On the Confluence page, insert a Jira Issue macro;
# On the macro's settings, click on *Display options*;
# On the *Columns to display* field, type the name that was given to the Jira custom field;
# Click on the *Insert* button;
# *Publish* the page;

h3. Expected Results 
* Confluence will list the options of that field that were checked on the Jira Issue, distinctly.

h3. Actual Results 
* Confluence displays the options that were checked on a long string, without differentiating which are the options separately.

h3.Workaround 
N/A

Today May 29th, after a 3 day weekend I see that someone has posted comments to a page.  I need to know what time the comment was made. The line below the comment states:
{code:java}
Reply Edit Delete Like May 25, 2018
{code}
Below the first comment is another comment.  And below that comment is:
{code:java}
Reply Edit Delete Like about an hour ago
{code}

Why are the hours, minutes, and seconds not displayed?
How about:
{code:java}
Reply Edit Delete Like May 25, 2018 at 5:32:00 PM
{code}
And 
{code:java}
Reply Edit Delete Like May 29th, 2018 at 8:32:13 AM (about an hour ago)
{code}

The time that comments are posted is important to us. "About 3 hours ago" is too vague.

h3. Summary 
* The select all/deselect all checkbox on a Jira Issue macro doesn't work properly.

h3. Environment 
* Firefox

h3. Steps to Reproduce 
# Create a page in Confluence;
# Add a Jira Issue macro to it;
# On the Jira Issue macro settings, type the filter to find your Jira issues;
# Check the box to select all/deselect all

h3. Expected Results 
* If you check the box to select all, all boxes of all Jira issues should be marked down;
* If you check the box to deselect all, all boxes of all Jira issues should be blank;

h3. Actual Results 
* The checkbox to select/deselect all issues doesn't mark/unmark the Jira issues brought by the filter.

h3.Workaround 
* This issue is not happening on Google Chrome.
